  "response_text": "The mean reserve biomass in the grazing system exhibits distinct trends over the simulated time steps. Initially, the biomass starts at approximately 90,000 units. In the early stages, from time step 0 to around time step 26, there is a noticeable decline in the mean reserve biomass, reaching a minimum value of approximately 84,114 units. This period is characterized by a significant decreasing trend. Following this decline, there is a transition phase where the biomass begins to recover. From around time step 26 onwards, the mean reserve biomass shows a consistent increasing trend. This recovery phase can be divided into several sub-phases where the rate of increase varies. Initially, the biomass increases rapidly, followed by a more gradual rise as it approaches a plateau. By the end of the simulation at time step 100, the mean reserve biomass reaches approximately 121,073 units. The overall trend indicates an initial decline in biomass followed by a robust recovery and stabilization at higher levels. The system demonstrates resilience as it recovers from the initial drop and achieves a new equilibrium with higher biomass levels."
}

